oc:kn_12b78c0d a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:SecurityImplication ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When structuring pages for B2B or enterprise audiences" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Enterprise/B2B pages require a dedicated security/compliance section and ROI/value quantification that consumer pages do not." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Enterprise buyers have different decision criteria (compliance, ROI, role-based use cases) that must be explicitly addressed." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_145e3913 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:KnownIssue ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing the problem/pain section" ;
    oc:directiveContent "The problem section must articulate the user's problem better than they can, creating a 'that's exactly my situation' recognition. Start with empathy phrases like 'You know the feeling...' or 'If you're like most [role]...'" ;
    oc:hasRationale "If visitors don't feel understood in the problem section, they won't trust the solution that follows." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_6b1b70ac a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing any landing page structure" ;
    oc:directiveContent "A landing page tells a story: Hero establishes value → Social proof builds trust → Problem creates recognition → Solution shows the path → Objections are handled → Final CTA closes with risk reversal." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Persuasion follows a narrative arc; skipping sections breaks the psychological journey from awareness to decision." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_73c79987 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When structuring any marketing page" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never build a landing page as a flat list of features (Hero → Feature 1 → Feature 2 → Feature 3 → CTA). This is a list, not a persuasive narrative." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Feature lists fail to address objections, create emotional connection, or guide the visitor through a decision journey." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_8376c901 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When choosing a headline formula for any page" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Match headline formula to strategy: use outcome-focused when the benefit is clear, problem-focused when pain is acute, audience-focused when targeting a specific segment, differentiation-focused when competing in a crowded market, proof-focused when credibility is the main barrier." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Different market positions require different persuasive angles; matching formula to strategy increases resonance." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_970594f9 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When selecting or writing testimonials for any page" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Testimonials must include specific results (e.g., 'increased conversions by 32%') with before/after context and role + company. Avoid vague praise like 'Great product!' or 'Love it!'" ;
    oc:hasRationale "Vague testimonials lack credibility; specific, attributed results are far more persuasive and trustworthy." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_9cde9044 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing the solution/benefits section of any page" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Include no more than 3-5 key benefits in the benefits section. Each benefit needs a headline (outcome), body (how it works in 1-2 sentences), and optional proof." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Too many benefits dilute impact; the headline-body-proof structure gives each benefit persuasive weight." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_aca76e4f a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing the 'How It Works' section" ;
    oc:directiveContent "How It Works should be exactly 3-4 numbered steps, each with a simple verb (Connect, Set up, Get) and an outcome. This reduces perceived complexity." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Numbered steps create a sense of progress and simplicity; too many steps increase perceived effort and reduce conversion." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

